    would rather, you can mark your bookmarks as private, making them viewable
    only by you.  The decision is yours;</li>
    <li>All public bookmarks are always visible, along with a count of how many
    people have bookmarked the same item.  This allows your to find new
    information that may also be of interest to you.  That's the power of the
    social aspect of connexions!</li>
   </ul>
  </div>
 </li><!-- question-answer } -->

 <li class='collapsable'><!-- question-answer { -->
  <h3 id='what_is_social_bookmarking'
      class='toggle faq-question<?= Connexions_Help::section_collapsed($this, 'what_is_social_bookmarking', true) ?>'><a href='<?= $url ?>/what_is_social_bookmarking' data-cache.collapsable='what_is_social_bookmarking_content'>What is social bookmarking?</a></h3>
  <div id='what_is_social_bookmarking_content'
       class='help-content faq-answer'>
   <p><b>Social bookmarking</b> is "a method for users to organize, store,
  manage and search for bookmarks of resources online.  Unlike file sharing,
  the <i>resources</i> themselves aren't shared, merly bookmarks that
      <i>reference</i> them." <sup>[<?=
      Connexions::wikipedia_a('Social_bookmarking', 'wikipedia') ?>]</sup></p>
   <p>In addition to saving references to online resources, connexions also
   allows bookmarks to contain a textual description, rating, be marked private
   and/or favorite, as well as have one or more tags associated with them.</p>
   <p>The tags associated with bookmarks are what make connexions a <?=
   Connexions::wikipedia_a('Folksonomy', 'folksonomy') ?>, allowing users to
   determine the form of organization required for their needs.  There is no
   forced heirarchy of terms that users must learn.  They are free to create
   their own as individuals, as ad-hoc collaborative groups, or even as
   structured groups.  It's completely up to the users.</p>
  </div>
 </li><!-- question-answer } -->

 <li class='collapsable'><!-- question-answer { -->
